'''Pierre Brasseur''' (21 June 1832 – 7 February 1918) was a [[Luxembourg]]ian entrepreneur, businessman, and mining magnate, being involved in founding a number of industrial concerns in southern Luxembourg.  Amongst them was one of the steel companies that would become [[ARBED]], and, after many mergers and consolidations, [[Arcelor Mittal]].

Pierre was a member of the [[Brasseur family]], born the eleventh son of Alexis Brasseur in [[Esch-sur-Alzette]].<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 31</ref>  Along with a number of other associates, Pierre founded the Society for the Extraction of Minerals of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg ({{lang-fr|Société pour l'Exploitation des Minières du Grand-Duché de Luxembourg}}).<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 31</ref> in 1861.  The following year, he was awarded a [[Concession (contract)|concession]] to mine an area of {{convert|77|ha|sqmi}} near [[Rumelange]], in Luxembourg's [[Red Lands]].<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 31</ref>  He was appointed [[Civil law notary|notary]] in Esch-sur-Alzette in 1864.

His success allowed him to establish in 1870 the Society of Blast Furnaces of Luxembourg ({{lang-fr|S.A. des Hauts Fourneaux Luxembourgeois}}), along with twenty-six other subscribers.  He was one of the members of the first administrative council of the company, which directed the company until 1874.<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 32</ref>  The company opened two [[blast furnace]]s in Esch in 1872 and 1873.  In about 1874, he left the administrative council.<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 32</ref>  However, his name would forever be attached to the furnaces in Esch.  After mergers with German operations, and expansion in Esch-sur-Alzette and into [[Alsace-Lorraine]], the company would become the second-largest industrial business in the [[Zollverein]] (after [[Krupp]]).<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 33</ref>  In 1920, the firm would become [[ARBED]], which would form a major part of [[Arcelor Mittal]], the world's largest steel-maker.

In 1875, he was appointed notary in [[Differdange]].  Brasseur was appointed director of mines in Dudelange, which were to become the Society of Blast Furnaces and Forges of Dudelange.  In 1894, he founded the first [[cement]] company in Luxembourg, at Rumelange, which became the Society of Blast Furnaces of Rumelange in 1897.  He died on 7 February 1918.<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 34</ref>

On 17 November 1864, he married Hélène Wurth,<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 31</ref> daughter of [[François-Xavier Wurth-Paquet]], who had been a famous Luxembourgian politician and [[Minister for Justice of Luxembourg|Administrator-General for Luxembourg]].  Pierre's family played a key role in politics itself.  His son, [[Xavier Brasseur|Xavier]], was a [[Socialist Party (Luxembourg)|Socialist]] member of the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] (1902–12).  Pierre's younger brother, [[Dominique Brasseur|Dominique]],  was also a [[deputy (legislator)|deputy]] (1866–99) and [[mayor of Luxembourg City]] (1891–94).  Dominique's son, and Pierre's nephew, [[Robert Brasseur|Robert]], was a deputy (1899–1925) and founder of the [[Liberal League (Luxembourg)|Liberal League]].<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 108</ref>

